data.description: Join us for a conversation with Dr. Nichole Garcia (Assistant Professor of Higher Education and College Student Affairs at Rutgers University) about her recent book Latinx Students in Higher Education (2021).  As a Chicana/Puerto Rican her research focuses on the intersections of race, Feminisms of Color, and Latinx/a/o communities in higher education. Specifically, she conducts comparative studies on Chicana/o ad Puerto Rican college-educated families to advance narratives of intergenerational achievement and college choice processes. Garcia is an alum of the Ronald E. McNair Post Baccalaureate Achievement program which she credits for putting her on the path to graduate school. She received her Ph.D. in Social Science and Comparative Education with a specialization in Race and Ethnic Studies from the University of California, Los Angeles. Garcia has published in Race, Ethnicity, and Education, The Journal of Latinos in Education, Journal of Hispanic Higher Education, and Frontiers. She is an avid blogger for Diverse Issues in Higher Education, and writes the college preparation column for Motivos, a bilingual magazine for Latinx high school students throughout the nation. Presented by CLAC as part of its Faculty Appreciation Series. Food and refreshments served.  This Faculty Appreciation Series is designed to highlight the work of Latinx/e faculty at Rutgers and allow students to interact with engaged faculty members in a comfortable setting outside of the classroom.

data.description: Please join us to see and discuss the Colombian documentary The Way Back in the Maloca, directed by Óscar Aponte. In the heart of the Amazon rainforest, the Murui-Muina people of Leguízamo, Colombia, defend their culture and traditions after surviving the genocide perpetrated by the rubber company Casa Arana. In a sound and visual journey through the rivers and jungles of Amazonia, The Way Back to the Maloca documents the life of the Murui-Muina people in night ceremonies, agricultural plots, malocas, classrooms, traditional dances, and daily conversations. Will the Murui-Muina people succeed in rescuing their ancestral knowledge and passing it down to the new generations? Óscar is an interdisciplinary scholar and filmmaker with a history, sociology, and anthropology background. Currently, he is a Ph.D. candidate in Latin American and Caribbean History at The Graduate Center of the City University of New York.
data.name: Film Screening and Discussion

data.description: Stories of Feminist Activism: My Voice, My Story, My Way Gather with us for 90 minutes of reflection, creativity, and impact. This experience will provide space for you to craft and create your activism story in your own way. Amedium that reflects your voice and experience (e.g., custom playlist, essay,prose, poetry, zine, video, performing arts, visual art, etc.) with a topic/theme (e.g.,voting rights, BLM, bodily autonomy, reproductive justice/rights, xenophobia,GBV, etc.) you are most enthusiastic about. Sixteen Stories. Feminists. Days is a testament to the power of the feminist voice, narrative, advocacy, activism, and collaboration. In recognition and celebration of the global initiative, 16 Days Campaign, the collaboration invites everyone who has engaged with feminist activism to join us in building a community around the purpose of activism and change. Fostering and bolstering a community of feminist activists. We hope this workshop inspires individuals to submit their story for the 2023 campaign or future campaigns! We invite you to learn more about S.H.E. Collective + Sixteen Stories campaign HERE. For additional information please email us at info@shecollectiveinc.com Workshop Objectives• Reveal and tune into your own voice• Choice to use your voice and story for advocacy/activism• Create a safe, creative space to craft your story• Connecting Sixteen Stories to 16 Days of Activism• Building a community of storytellers & activists• Embrace our stories as catalysts for change and transformationInspirational Items to Bring• Digital or hard copy photos• Recipe• Computer, phone• Favorite list of songs• Favorite list of books Provided Materials• Paper• Pens, crayons, pencils• Magazines• Music source for playlist
data.name: Stories of Feminist Activism: My Voice, My Story, My Way

data.description: Join us and learn more about the Master of Business and Science degree program. Enjoy light refreshments, a program presentation, and a lively Q&A. Faculty advisors and program staff will be on hand to discuss the program, academic and professional goals. This unique program combines advanced, STEM-based education with professionally guided business instruction—enabling graduates to step confidently and adeptly into the STEM workforce. The MBS degree provides - externship, internship, executive coaching, an alumni-student mentoring program, professional development, colloquium and more! Please register for this event here.

data.name: OPEN HOUSE: “4+1” BS/MBS Program - Science Meets Business!

data.description: Celebrate the end of the academic year by joining Douglass staff, the Voorhees Choir, and fellow students for the annual Sacred Path Ceremony. One of Douglass' oldest traditions, the Sacred Path ceremony recognizes student achievement and fosters Douglass's unique community. Join your fellow Douglass classmates, alumnae, friends, and family as each class is honored with a symbol representing the different class years. After you receive your charm, head to the ceremonial fires on the sacred path to make a wish!  Students should show their pride by wearing their class year colors (first years wear white, sophomores wear pink, juniors wear red, and seniors wear black). Every student will receive a charm, a token representing her class. All Douglass students, family, faculty, and alumnae are welcome! Refreshments will be provided at Ludwig immediately following the ceremony.  *Students in Knowledge & Power will receive 2 points towards their Douglass event requirements*
data.name: Sacred Path 2024
data.organizationName: Traditional Events at Douglass Residential College - DRC
